body:
me: i have an extremely important life update
my poor bedeviled friends and family: is it med school news???
me: oh yeah i got into one. but more importantly, i started watching spectacular spider man (2008) which only ran for two 13-episode seasons before it was canceled which is a god damn travesty because it’s possibly the best superhero cartoon out there. 1) it actually has a cohesive and continuous plot and story development instead of relying solely on surface level monsters of the week. 2) it actually shows the consequences of peter’s alter ego on his relationships without treating it as a joke. 3) it delves into the psyche of why peter

summary: gimme a spider-man continuity where everyone wearing the webs has been foudn worthy of continuing the legacy of the first of...
body:
gimme a spider-man continuity where everyone wearing the webs has been foudn worthy of continuing the legacy of the first of them all

the first trickster, the first hero in all the world. the first one to beat bullies and brutality by being clever, winning all the stories to him and changing what it meant to actually win

the first spider, Anansi himself

and each and every Spider-Man, across the multiverse, whether they get their powers with magic or through scientific accidents, its all accidents, really, but it ultimately stems from him

them being who they are is what makes them perfect to be modern heroes, carrying on the legacy of the first trickster

but mostly is that every. Single. ONE OF THEM is just a massive human disaster, even the ones who aren’t actually human, and that is just such perfect emulation of him that Anansi can’t help but give them a high five. With webs on, because he’s gotta be a little bit of a smart ass, its just how he do

summary: a thing i noticed about Peter B. Parker is that everything about him is conveyed, through the aesthetics of the movie, in sorrow...
body:
a thing i noticed about Peter B. Parker is that everything about him is conveyed, through the aesthetics of the movie, in sorrow and exhaustion

his movements are a lot… not slower, not awkward, but weary. It takes emotional effort from him all the time. His colors are significantly more drab and gray than Miles or Gwen (who otherwise share his animation aesthetic, perhaps conveying that their universes are very akin). His expressions are mostly flat, even his comedic moments sound like he’s having to put a lot of effort into it.

He radiates exhaustion, wearinesss. He is a tired, broken man.

Until, that is

he puts on the mask.

and it’s not him having to be Peter B. Parker, professional wreck and burned out hero damaged by the lifestyle. He’s the amazing, the ultimate, the spectacular Spider-Man.

the instant he puts on the mask, everything bout him suddenly changes:

his drab colors are bright. his expressions go from ‘tired and doing my best to just slog through’ to the bright and animated you expect from Spider-Man. even his movements become a lot more flowing and fun

he is a sad and broken man who is just done with everything hurting, but the moment he puts on that mask, he’s your friendly neighborhood Spider-Man again
